content.description: Challenged my jambing skills beyond their limit. Footwork, too. I was taught to crack climb by the late Matt Clow, and named the route to honor him. I guess Rusty didn’t like the name so he renamed it.Starts in a cave. I think #3 Camelot worked inside the bottom of the roof. Off hands/fists turns the roof. Eases up a lot after that.
content.protection: #3 and smaller camalots. I don’t think #4 was needed.
content.location: Keep going right beyond the Main Wall. You’ll see it.

content.description: Climb past the chossy limestone/conglomerate ledge just left of a bolt. Big fingers start to a wide crack just below a bulge. After pulling onto a ledge that is likely covers in bat guano, climb the hands to a stellar fingers crack. Well work putting up with the bat guano if you like finger cracks.
content.protection: Up to #3 Camalot. Double fingers may be useful.
content.location: Just left of the Bolt on the Main Wall. Belay from the sandy limestone diving board.

content.description: Straight shot to the top -- roof crack to the inside corner, then stem through the twin cracks to the anchor.
content.location: Starts in the handcrack in a small roof, just above the rotten band.
